// ch05 §5.12: "A by-value capture is an ordinary owned member, copied or
// moved in exactly like initializing a class member from an argument."
// The capture happens at closure-*creation* time, not at call time: `x`
// is captured as 5 here, so mutating the outer `x` afterward must not
// affect what the closure returns when called later.
//
// This test needs the closure to outlive the statement that mutates `x`,
// which means it must be given a name -- `auto` (C++11 local-variable
// type deduction) is the only way to spell a closure's own unnameable
// type, exactly as in real C++. This is assumed to already work like
// real C++ (ch00 §2/§6: nothing is restricted unless a chapter says so),
// since it isn't called out as excluded anywhere in ch06.
int main() {
    int x = 5;
    auto f = [x]() { return x; };
    x = 10;
    return f();
}
